Once we have the rig prepared, we can build the connection between the skeleton and the mesh by binding skin. Then, we adjust the skin weight on the mesh to properly allocate the influences from the joints. This is a very late step in the rigging process if not the last. 

We can find bind skin under the skin menu. The process is to first select the parent joint (cog joint/pelvis joint), then select the mesh (if there is more than one, ctrl select them all), then click apply. 

Next, we look at the option box of the bind skin tool. We can tell maya to bind the selected mesh to joint hierarchy/selected joints/object hierarchy. If joint hierarchy option allows us to only select the parent joint, yet taking itself and all its child joints into calculation. However, selected joints option would only take the selected ones into calculation. A way to bind them is to separate the mesh into different parts, and use selected joints option to bind each part separately, this way can prevent skin weight allocated to places we don't want. Object hierarchy option allows mesh to bind to objects that are not joints, which is rarely used for game. 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Bind method has closest distance/closest in hierarchy/heat map/geodesic voxel options. Normally, we try closest distance. If it is too bad, then we try heat map and geodesic voxel, which are newer algorithms. But all of them are just providing a start point, we need to clean up the skin weight no matter which one we use. So just select the one that gives you the best starting point. 

Max influences option tells maya how many joints at max are allowed to influence one vertex. In many cases, 4 is enough.
